We aimed for a 4 course meal each ... but ended up leaving with a 5 course meal for most of us. I was talked into getting dessert and we shared it as a group. I have never been to a place where I've enjoyed every plate, every course,..every .. anything! At GD, I enjoyed not only my experience, the environment, the service .. but every bit of the food as well. I'm not entirely sure if words could even explain our experience here! My friends and I all had different courses but we enjoyed everything we had. Tried bits and pieces of each other's plates and figured out what we would order for next time because there is a definite next time! What I Had (Pictures Available) : 1. I was extremely excited to dig in so I wasn't exactly paying attention to what my first dish was ... 2. Don't get me wrong here, it was a very good meal and I liked every bite that was placed in front of me! The reason this is 3/5 stars is that for a place requiring a reservation to accommodate my group needing 60 days out and reading review after review that this is a top restaurant in the country I was not left all that impressed by the offering on the menu or the food itself when it was presented. I had the risotto with rock shrimp and crab and yes, this dish knocked it out of the park as far as flavor and appearance goes! If every item I ordered was on par with this dish it would be a 5 star rating. I had mine with truffle over top and it was great. Up next was waiters recommendation from the seafood section which was the roasted lobster with potato purée (they are known for this he said). There was supposedly mushrooms and edamame as part of this dish but if that was the case it was not something visually available for me to see. The lobster was good, nothing over the top as far as flavor goes or as far as presentation went. The potato purée really was just that... a cooked potato puréed with really no other flavors that I was able to pull out. Lastly I had a filet mignon cooked medium rare. The steak was good with nice flavor but it really was no different than if I dined at a steakhouse where I reside in Scottsdale (dominicks, steak 44, city hall, etc) it was to come prepared with gnocchi, Swiss chard, and butter. There were 3 pieces of gnocchi - they taste fine, nothing worth writing more about. As far as the waiters statements went he said that going for less in the way of the number of courses was smarter as their dishes were rather large in portion. In my opinion the dishes were a bit larger than say a studio at montage (laguna) or a binkleys in Phoenix, however, the difference is the two restaurants I just mentioned also bring out a taster from the chef between every single course - nothing of the sort at Gary danko so you'd have to expect a slightly larger portion to become full. Last up was the butter cake - basically it was a muffin, not at all soft as butter cake I've had at many places tends to be and it lacked the butter cake taste I crave. I felt as though I was eating a muffin with a bit more sugar in it with 3 cinnamon apple slices on top, and a pool of berry reduction to drag it through for more flavor. It was a tasty dessert but I took two bites and was good to leave the remainder for the others at my table to try. I had several friends both local to San Fran and others who frequently dine at higher end places ask me the following day just how amazing it was and I let them know that they could expect a very good meal with a great selection of wine to choose from but not to worry if they overlook it for a handful of other restaurants instead. Maybe I simply ordered the wrong items or all the reviews and critically acclaimed articles left me expecting something that would be groundbreaking in flavor/presentation/ingredient choices, but for me this was a let down on many levels.

It's not easy for restaurants to stay relevant in San Francisco, a city that has a plethora of dining options and is known for it's yummy food. Gary Danko has managed to do just that! Regardless, we're still talking about this wonderful meal and it occurred nearly two months ago!

They also gave each of us a parting gift in the form of a pumpkin coffee cake. Sadly... the amuse bouche, oysters, and coffee cake were the only winners of the evening. It's funny how their complimentary items outshone their food. LOL.... Would we return to Gary Danko? No. We didn't enjoy most of our time there and weren't impressed with most of our orders. Once a San Francisco stalwart for above average cuisine with spectacular service, Restaurant Gary Danko has lost its charm and magic. One of the traditionally great characteristics of Gary Danko used to be the idea each individual at a table could choose 3, 4, or 5 items off the menu and seamlessly, the food would be brought out in such a way that no one would have to wait. Over the years, Gary Danko seems to be slipping and at our last visit struggled to live up to this promise, with 4 out of 5 guests waiting over 60 minutes between the first and second item. Worse, the staff seemed to ignore this elephant in the room choosing to avert their eyes as they walked by. A proactive "we're sorry we are running late" rather than a defensive excuse would have been more professional. While the overly salty food might simply be a throwback to an older age of cuisine, unless you're specifically looking for this kind of food, the dilapidated service makes this an average experience in today's San Francisco.

I was so happy to celebrate my birthday with the husband at Gary Danko. I totally am in love with GD. My husband and I both decided to go with 5 coures of the tasting menu because we wanted to try as many as we could. And we basically shared everything. So I was able to eat all 10 courses. Muahhahaha ;-D Lobster Melon Salad and Dungeness Crab Salad- both of them are so refreshing and delicious. Lobster meat and crab meat were very fresh and high quality. I love both of the salad dishes. They were awesomely delicious! Glazed Oysters- OMG. this dish gave me food orgasm. It was sooo delicious. Words can't describe what I tasted. Seared Scallops- The scallops were cooked just perfect. It was very tasty. I've had very good scallops before in Portland, so this was not too wow for me. But still, yummy! Risotto with shrimps and dungeness crab- I typically don't like risotto, but this one changed my mind about risotto. It is rich but very good. Shrimp and crab meat blended in with risotto with corns perfectly. Roast Main Lobster- The lobster meat is no doubt super fresh and high quality. But this is actually the less impressed dish that I had at GD. Squab - I never had squab before, so i wanted to give it a try. The meat is tender and cooked to medium rare. Flavor was very different. It could be good to certain people but could be bad for those who don't eat various types of food from different cultures. Bison - Again, I've always had beef all my life but never had bison before. It was not different from beef. The meat was very tender, perfectly cooked. Awesome. I just don't really like the pea puree part of the dish. Lemon Pepper Duck - WOW. I never had duck this good in my entire life. The meat was so lean and perfectly flavored and cooked. Delicious!! Chocolate Souffle' - YUM!!!! In addition to all these 10 dishes, we had 2 amuse bouches: 1 soup and 1 canape, complimentary cookies and chocolate birthday cake and a take home banana bread. Service was truly top notch at Gary Danko. All the servers at our table were super friendly, informative, attentive, professional. From the moment we stepped out of the car entering the restaurant 'til driving off from the restaurant, there was nothing that could have done better. Every single person at GD has done their job awesomely. I can't wait to come back to GD. It is now my favorite restaurant!!!!!

GD really hit all the marks for a superlative restaurant. Amazing service, delicious food and impeccable ambiance. The maitre ds are all super knowledgeable about the menu, can give their recommendations for the combinations of prix fixe menus and constantly come around making sure you're taken care of. Also, they're very patient considering we were at the table a half hour after they closed. Food-wise, these were my favorites: - The foie gras. Holy crap, I wish I'd had it sooner. I'm told it's tough to screw up a foie gras dish so take this recommendation with a grain of salt. Nevertheless, the dish was like eating savory gelato. The liver was so tender, yet crispy. Thankfully, it was paired with caramelized red onions and pears to cut the heaviness of the foie gras with sweetness and acid. So good. - Artisinal cheeses. I know it seems strange, but the cheese they offer are unlike anything you've probably experienced. Lovely strong cheeses paired with fruit and nutty bread. Definitely suggest this in combination with some heavier dishes. Also, they were definitely spot on with their recommendations. Also great dishes: - Venison. The first time I ate at Gary Danko was 4 years ago, and it still ranks as one of my all-time faves in San Francisco. I don't know of any other Michelin-starred restaurant that will let you (nay, encourages you!) to choose 5 meat entree courses for your entire prix fixe meal. No appetizers, no desserts. Just meat. Also, I decided to splurge and added white truffles to this dish for an extra $35. It looked great, but the flavor was veeery subtle. Not worth the money, if you ask me. 3) Seared sea scallops - always delicious, although this time, the scallops had a very strong fishy taste to them. Surprising, and not that pleasant 4) Seared filet of beef with swiss chard - this was delicious. Cooked perfectly 5) Lemon pepper duck with duck hash - this was my most favorite dish of the night. They even used the duck skin to make crunch crackling. Amazing 6) Chocolate praline parfait with bourbon sauce Also, because it was my birthday, the restaurant also gave us another freebie dessert, a chocolate mousse cake. Needless to say, I was stuffed (and very happy) by the end of the meal.

A solid 4 stars but not 5 in my book. Maybe it was the hype (and the high expectations that came along with it). Give La Foret in Almaden a shot if you are into fine dining. IMHO, I think La Foret is better priced with a superior menu with larger portions! My friend had told me that this was the best restaurant in San Francisco so I had to give it a try. Chocolate Souffle - 9/10 Service - 10/10 All in all, I think my expectations were a bit high for the "best restaurant in SF". If I had to choose again, I would probably pick somewhere else to splurge $400.

    Don't get me wrong here, it was a very good meal and I liked every bite that was placed in front of me!

    The reason this is 3/5 stars is that for a place requiring a reservation to accommodate my group needing 60 days out and reading review after review that this is a top restaurant in the country I was not left all that impressed by the offering on the menu or the food itself when it was presented.

    I had the risotto with rock shrimp and crab and yes, this dish knocked it out of the park as far as flavor and appearance goes! If every item I ordered was on par with this dish it would be a 5 star rating. I had mine with truffle over top and it was great.

    Up next was waiters recommendation from the seafood section which was the roasted lobster with potato purée (they are known for this he said). There was supposedly mushrooms and edamame as part of this dish but if that was the case it was not something visually available for me to see. The lobster was good, nothing over the top as far as flavor goes or as far as presentation went. The potato purée really was just that... a cooked potato puréed with really no other flavors that I was able to pull out.

    Lastly I had a filet mignon cooked medium rare. The steak was good with nice flavor but it really was no different than if I dined at a steakhouse where I reside in Scottsdale (dominicks, steak 44, city hall, etc) it was to come prepared with gnocchi, Swiss chard, and butter. There were 3 pieces of gnocchi - they taste fine, nothing worth writing more about.

    As far as the waiters statements went he said that going for less in the way of the number of courses was smarter as their dishes were rather large in portion. In my opinion the dishes were a bit larger than say a studio at montage (laguna) or a binkleys in Phoenix, however, the difference is the two restaurants I just mentioned also bring out a taster from the chef between every single course - nothing of the sort at Gary danko so you'd have to expect a slightly larger portion to become full.

    Last up was the butter cake - basically it was a muffin, not at all soft as butter cake I've had at many places tends to be and it lacked the butter cake taste I crave. I felt as though I was eating a muffin with a bit more sugar in it with 3 cinnamon apple slices on top, and a pool of berry reduction to drag it through for more flavor. It was a tasty dessert but I took two bites and was good to leave the remainder for the others at my table to try.

    I had several friends both local to San Fran and others who frequently dine at higher end places ask me the following day just how amazing it was and I let them know that they could expect a very good meal with a great selection of wine to choose from but not to worry if they overlook it for a handful of other restaurants instead.

    Maybe I simply ordered the wrong items or all the reviews and critically acclaimed articles left me expecting something that would be groundbreaking in flavor/presentation/ingredient choices, but for me this was a let down on many levels.

    The nice thing about this place is you can order 3 course for $88 without a dessert, so only $88 for a foie gras dish, a (half) lobster and a (small) decent steak is very good value even if just for the ingredients.

    But the food is underwhelming, don't expect anything spectacular.

    Gary Danko is a classic spot. It's a great value and the menu is SUPER FLEXIBLE. We loved the fact that we each can choose from a 3, 4 or 5-course meal on top of the tasting menu. In addition, we  didn't have to have the same number of courses  (like most places) and we each can choose whatever we wanted for those 3-5 courses (i.e.... all courses is a different dessert, no dessert in the courses, or repeat the same entree for all courses). Service was good and we were seated promptly despite running 20 minutes late due to traffic. We drove 1.5 hours from SJ.

    For 5 courses, it's about $120 and it's a good value. However, we weren't impressed with the caliber of food.

    Amuse bouche - Very tasty - It was some kind of vegetable soup that had a wonderful depth.
    I ordered:

    Drink: Old Fashion - Disappointing - was full of ice cubes, and had cherries in it! I usually have it with one giant cube of ice, rye whiskey, and orange zest at all the bars I frequented.

    Foie Gras - Barely OK - It was slightly overcooked. Didn't taste buttery enough and didn't seem fresh.

    Oysters with caviar - Very tasty - Oysters were cooked perfectly and the caviar complemented it. I should have ordered 3 more courses of this!

    Lobster - Disappointing - Bland and flavorless. It was very very prettily plated.

    Seabass - JUST AWFUL - Cardinal Sin of cooking = Fished was completely cooked through and falling apart on the plate before I even ran my fork through it. The sauce didn't save it.

    BF ordered some of the same dishes I had but also ordered:

    Bison - Disappointing - It was a little dry, but ok.

    Scallops - OK- It was cooked nicely but too salty.

    We ordered a glass of the Ladoucette Pinot Noir that tasted very flat and had a glass of the Emrich Riesling which was just okay.

    Overall, we would have given them 2.5 stars, but they were very thoughtful and brought us a complimentary mousse dessert for the BF's bday coupled with mignardises (plate of sweets). They were good. They also gave each of us a parting gift in the form of a pumpkin coffee cake.

    Sadly... the amuse bouche, oysters, and coffee cake were the only winners of the evening. It's funny how their complimentary items outshone their food. LOL.... Would we return to Gary Danko? No. We didn't enjoy most of our time there and weren't impressed with most of our orders.

    The food isn't bad, but it wasn't great. I would still choose this place over Michael Mina in Vegas. LOL...

    10/8/2017

    Once a San Francisco stalwart for above average cuisine with spectacular service, Restaurant Gary Danko has lost its charm and magic.  One of the traditionally great characteristics of Gary Danko used to be the idea each individual at a table could choose 3, 4, or 5 items off the menu and seamlessly, the food would be brought out in such a way that no one would have to wait.  Over the years, Gary Danko seems to be slipping and at our last visit struggled to live up to this promise, with 4 out of 5 guests waiting over 60 minutes between the first and second item.  Worse, the staff seemed to ignore this elephant in the room choosing to avert their eyes as they walked by.  A proactive "we're sorry we are running late" rather than a defensive excuse would have been more professional.

    While the overly salty food might simply be a throwback to an older age of cuisine, unless you're specifically looking for this kind of food, the dilapidated service makes this an average experience in today's San Francisco.

    I was so happy to celebrate my birthday with the husband at Gary Danko. I totally am in love with GD. I did have high expectation for it since it wasn't easy to get reservation and the hype was really up there. But it's totally worth it, and GD does live up to the hype.

    Lobster Melon Salad and Dungeness Crab Salad- both of them are so refreshing and delicious. Lobster meat and crab meat were very fresh and high quality. I love both of the salad dishes. They were awesomely delicious!

    Glazed Oysters- OMG. this dish gave me food orgasm. It was sooo delicious. Words can't describe what I tasted.

    Seared Scallops- The scallops were cooked just perfect. It was very tasty. I've had very good scallops before in Portland, so this was not too wow for me. But still, yummy!

    Risotto with shrimps and dungeness crab- I typically don't like risotto, but this one changed my mind about risotto. It is rich but very good. Shrimp and crab meat blended in with risotto with corns perfectly.

    Roast Main Lobster- The lobster meat is no doubt super fresh and high quality. But this is actually the less impressed dish that I had at GD.

    Squab - I never had squab before, so i wanted to give it a try. The meat is tender and cooked to medium rare. Flavor was very different. It could be good to certain people but could be bad for those who don't eat various types of food from different cultures.

    Bison - Again, I've always had beef all my life but never had bison before. It was not different from beef. The meat was very tender, perfectly cooked. Awesome. I just don't really like the pea puree part of the dish.

    Lemon Pepper Duck - WOW. I never had duck this good in my entire life. The meat was so lean and perfectly flavored and cooked. Delicious!!

    Chocolate Souffle' - YUM!!!!

    In addition to all these 10 dishes, we had 2 amuse bouches: 1 soup and 1 canape, complimentary cookies and chocolate birthday cake and a take home banana bread.

    Service was truly top notch at Gary Danko. All the servers at our table were super friendly, informative, attentive, professional. From the moment we stepped out of the car entering the restaurant 'til driving off from the restaurant, there was nothing that could have done better. Every single person at GD has done their job awesomely.

    I can't wait to come back to GD. It is now my favorite restaurant!!!!!

    GD really hit all the marks for a superlative restaurant. Amazing service, delicious food and impeccable ambiance. The maitre ds are all super knowledgeable about the menu, can give their recommendations for the combinations of prix fixe menus and constantly come around making sure you're taken care of. Also, they're very patient considering we were at the table a half hour after they closed.

    Food-wise, these were my favorites:
    - The foie gras. Holy crap, I wish I'd had it sooner. I'm told it's tough to screw up a foie gras dish so take this recommendation with a grain of salt. Nevertheless, the dish was like eating savory gelato. The liver was so tender, yet crispy. Thankfully, it was paired with caramelized red onions and pears to cut the heaviness of the foie gras with sweetness and acid. So good.

    - Artisinal cheeses. I know it seems strange, but the cheese they offer are unlike anything you've probably experienced. Lovely strong cheeses paired with fruit and nutty bread. Definitely suggest this in combination with some heavier dishes. Also, they were definitely spot on with their recommendations.

    Also great dishes:
    - Venison. Never had it, love the slightly gamey flavor with a tender texture. Really nice with the chestnut spaetzle, clementines and cabbage. Great complement of meaty, nutty and fruity flavos.

    - Duck breast. Sooo tender. Combined with duck hash and some 'chokes. The hash was kinda regular by itself, but together, they was super ducky and delicious.

    - Oysters. Glazed oysters were nice, especially with the caviar. Buuut, the dish was really small and the lettuce sauce didn't really do anything for me.

    - Grilled pineapple with crepes. Awesome caramelized taste with great acid and nice contrast in texture. I don't know if it's really worth the extra $6 though.

    My group got drinks as well, and they were great! I had a good Sazerac so I recommend that for you, too.

    They overheard that it was my friend's bday so he also got a ganache cake and some bite-size dessert pastries. Everything was great so extra points for service.
